# Sovereign Cloud Agent Rules

## Design Philosophy

- **Rapid initialisation**: `make check-env && make upload-acm-chart && make init-central-argo` = zero-to-platform.
- **Makefile portability**: every OpenShift mutation is a `make` target; rerunnable on any cluster by setting env vars.
- **Make target files**: each make target lives in its own file under `make/*.mk`; the root `Makefile` imports them.
- **OCP Appliance end-goal**: bootstrap pipeline will produce a versioned OCP Appliance image embedding all platform components for sovereign/air-gapped deployment.
- **Developer sandbox**: clone bootstrap → set env → `make` = isolated dev cluster, no shared cluster needed.
- **OC read-only**: `oc`/`kubectl` for investigation only; all mutations via `make` or ArgoCD.

## Non-negotiable constraints

- **Repo boundary**: modify only `bootstrap/` and `architecture/`. Never write to `/` (workspace root).
- **Validate**: run `helm lint` before marking chart work done.
- **Make for oc**: all OpenShift CLI interactions must go through `make` targets.
- **GitOps**: after `make init-central-argo`, all installs must be ArgoCD ApplicationSet driven.
- **Secrets**: all credentials via environment variables, passed through `helm --set`. Never hardcode.
- **Git**: commit and push freely. Commit messages: `<type>: <description>`.
- **No git history**: never use git log, git blame, or commit history for context. Only look at the current state of files.
- **Docs**: update `bootstrap/README.md`, Makefile help, and `architecture/docs/` on every meaningful change.
- **Iterate**: deploy → test → fix loop until `Synced + Healthy`. Debug with `oc` read commands.
- **Diagrams**: use Mermaid in `architecture/docs/`. Keep each diagram small and focused (max ~15 nodes). Split complex diagrams into multiple files.
- **Security**: after any chart or Makefile change, review `architecture/hardeningcheck/security-assessment.md` and update if findings change.
- **Architecture**: always follow `architecture/docs/` as the source of truth for platform topology.

## Human-readability rules

- **No large files**: any file above 500 lines must be split into multiple files.
- **No large diagrams**: split complex diagrams into multiple small, focused diagrams (max ~15 nodes each).
- **Simple language**: documentation should be understandable by non-technical stakeholders where possible.
- **One concern per file**: each file should have a single clear purpose.

## ArgoCD rules

- **Self-heal**: all ArgoCD Applications must have `selfHeal: true` in their sync policy.
- **Prune**: all ArgoCD Applications must have `prune: true` to remove orphaned resources.
- **Always in sync**: if any ArgoCD Application is not `Synced + Healthy`, investigate and fix immediately.
- **Dynamic plugins**: always enable ArgoCD dynamic plugins when available (e.g., `argocd-vault-plugin`, UI plugins).

## OCI / Quay rules

- **Robot read-only**: the Quay robot account (`hybrid-sovereign+pull`) must have **read-only** access on all repositories in the `hybrid-sovereign` organization. Use the admin token (`OCI_REGISTRY_TOKEN`) for write operations (repo creation, chart push).
- **Chart push uses admin token**: `make upload-acm-chart` authenticates with the admin token for push, not the robot.

## Required Environment Variables

All of the following **must** be set before any `make` target is executed. Never hardcode these values.
`make check-env` verifies all 12 at once and tests logins.

### Central Cluster
| Variable | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `OCP_CENTRAL_SERVER` | Central cluster API URL |
| `OCP_CENTRAL_USERNAME` | Central cluster login username |
| `OCP_CENTRAL_PASSWORD` | Central cluster login password |

### Services Cluster
| Variable | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `OCP_SERVICES_SERVER` | Services cluster API URL |
| `OCP_SERVICES_USERNAME` | Services cluster login username |
| `OCP_SERVICES_PASSWORD` | Services cluster login password |

### OCI Registry (admin)
| Variable | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `OCI_REGISTRY` | Quay registry hostname or full URL (e.g. `https://quay.io/organization/myorg`) |
| `OCI_REGISTRY_TOKEN` | Admin bearer token (used to create repos and push charts) |

### OCI Registry (robot/read-only)
| Variable | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `OCI_ROBOT_USERNAME` | Robot account username — read-only access to pull charts |
| `OCI_ROBOT_PASSWORD` | Robot account token |

### Derived Variables (computed by Makefile)
| Variable | Derivation |
|---|---|
| `OCI_HOST` | Hostname extracted from `OCI_REGISTRY` |
| `OCI_NAMESPACE` | Organization from URL path (defaults to `sovereign` if not a URL) |

### Git
| Variable | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `GITHUB_URL` | Repository base URL |
| `GITHUB_TOKEN` | Personal access token (repo scope) |

## Cluster Prerequisites (one-time, manual)

Before running any bootstrap phase, both clusters must have:
1. **OpenShift 4.x** installed
2. **ArgoCD (OpenShift GitOps)** installed and accessible

## Repository Folder Layout

```
bootstrap/
├── Makefile                    # Imports all make/*.mk files
├── make/                       # Individual make target files
│   ├── check-env.mk           # check-env target
│   ├── upload-acm-chart.mk    # upload-acm-chart target
│   └── init-central-argo.mk   # init-central-argo target
└── helm/
    ├── charts/
    │   └── rhacm/              # Standalone RHACM chart — pushed to OCI by make upload-acm-chart
    ├── central/                # App-of-Apps chart → deployed into central cluster
    │   └── templates/
    │       └── rhacm-application.yaml  # Application sourcing rhacm from OCI
    └── init/                   # Bootstrap entry-point chart
        └── templates/
            ├── applicationset.yaml           # Drives central + services app-of-apps
            ├── git-repo-secret.yaml          # ArgoCD git credential secret
            └── services-cluster-secret.yaml  # Registers services cluster with ArgoCD

architecture/
├── docs/
│   ├── 01-overview.md         # Platform overview
│   ├── 02-bootstrap-flow.md   # Bootstrap sequence (simple flowchart)
│   ├── 03-central-cluster.md  # Central cluster components
│   ├── 04-services-cluster.md # Services cluster components
│   └── 05-oci-registry.md     # OCI registry interaction
└── hardeningcheck/
    └── security-assessment.md # Security assessment + CIS gaps + remediation list
```

## Key rules for agents working in each directory

- `helm/charts/rhacm` — after any change run `helm lint helm/charts/rhacm`; bump `Chart.yaml` version; re-run `make upload-acm-chart`.
- `helm/central` — run `helm lint` after every chart change; update `values.yaml` chart version reference when the OCI chart is bumped.
- `helm/init` — this is the bootstrap entry-point; changes here affect both clusters simultaneously; always test with `helm template` before pushing.
- `make/*.mk` — each target in its own file; keep the root Makefile as a thin importer.
- `architecture/docs/` — keep diagrams small and split across files. One diagram per concept.
- `architecture/hardeningcheck/security-assessment.md` — update findings after any security-impacting change.

## Make Targets

| Target | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `make check-env` | Verify all 12 required env vars are set AND test logins (OCP + OCI) |
| `make upload-acm-chart` | Create Quay OCI repo and push the chart (uses admin token) |
| `make init-central-argo` | Log in to central cluster, deploy `helm/init`, trigger app-of-apps |

## Bootstrap Execution Order

```
1. make check-env          ← always run first (validates vars + tests logins)
2. make upload-acm-chart   ← push RHACM chart to OCI (before ArgoCD tries to sync it)
3. make init-central-argo  ← deploy init chart → ApplicationSet fires → RHACM + all apps install
```
